<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06067101 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06067101 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  PAST; JUDGE; DEATH; COURT; BEHAVIOR; ABUSE; RULING  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A hearing on the courtroom and out-of-court behavior of the late SuperiorCourt Judge Bert B. Bailey of Colusa County has resulted in a finding of 34misconduct incidents.;    But the next step, a hearing before the stateCommission on Judicial Performance, at which Bailey could have contested thefindings, will not be taken because he is dead, the disciplinary commissionsaid Tuesday in a cursory prepared statement.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  California News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  DEAD JUDGE COMMITTED MISCONDUCT, PANEL SAYS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Bailey, 57, hanged himself a month ago in his court chambers' anteroom. Hewas appointed to the bench in 1987 by then-Gov. George Deukmejian afterpracticing law in Colusa for 23 years.;    The probe of Bailey's officialconduct, which began before his suicide, was prompted by complaints about hisbehavior on and off the bench.;    Two years ago, a California Highway Patrolofficer stopped Bailey for speeding and suspicion of drunken driving. Herefused to take a field sobriety test but passed a blood-alcohol test at thecounty jail.;    He later filed a complaint with the Highway Patrol, seeking$500 in damages and alleging that he had been beaten during his arrest. TheHighway Patrol countered with a tape-recording made by the arresting officer.;   After the patrol and the state Board of Control denied Bailey's claims,District Attorney John Poyner charged him with filing a false crime report andfalse claim, charges that were ultimately dismissed.;    The Commission onJudicial Performance did not elaborate on its three-week probe except to saythat a panel of three masters found 21 incidents of &quot;willful misconduct&quot; and13 incidents of &quot;conduct prejudicial to the administration of justice.&quot;;   The panel consisted of two retired judges and one active judge.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  